@node not25 "QUAKE 1 SOURCE CODE RELEASED"

                          QUAKE 1 SOURCE CODE RELEASED
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Rumours were floating around about the release of the Quake 1 source code at the
end of the year. This has become a reality because Id Software have put the
complete source code for winquake, glquake, quakeworld, and glquakeworld into
the public domain.

The code is all licensed under the terms of the GPL (gnu public license). You
should read the entire license, but the gist of it is that you can do anything
you want with the code, including sell your new version. The catch is that if
you distribute new binary versions, you are required to make the entire source
code available for free to everyone.

All of the Quake data files remain copyrighted and licensed under the original
terms, so you cannot redistribute data from the original game, but if you do a
true total conversion, you can create a standalone game based on this code.

If you never actually bought a complete version of Quake, you might want to
rummage around in a local software bargain bin for one of the originals, or
perhaps buy the 68k version made by clickBOOM time ago.

Probably the first WarpOS version we will see will be the one by Steffen
Hausser, which is expected to be released on Sunday, December 27th.
Unfortunately, this version will not support Warp3D, as this will require a lot
of effort. Probably, we will see a Warp3D version in Spring 2000.

More info at http://www.idsoftware.com/q1source/.
