@node not30 "COSA PROGRESS UPDATE FOR DECEMBER 1999"

                     COSA PROGRESS UPDATE FOR DECEMBER 1999

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

                              COSA PROGRESS UPDATE
                               DECEMBER 24, 1999

                       An Open Letter - December 24, 1999
                       By COSA President, Steve Crietzman

Introduction

Since our first open letter to the Amiga community, there has been a great deal
of progress and many behind-the-scenes changes to the internal structure and
focus of COSA. We want to keep the community up-to-date on these changes, and so
after the new year we will provide much more detailed information on our plans
for the new millennium.

We would like to use this update to touch on an area that has not received much
discussion to date, and that is our talks with Tom Schmidt. Since so few people
get to talk with him, we thought it would be helpful for the community to hear
our perspective on the man who is now at the helm of Amiga.

This update focuses on our talks with Tom Schmidt. The next update, after the
new year, will discuss our plans for the new millenium, and hopefully, by the
third update two weeks later, we will have something solid to report from Amiga
Inc. We will keep you informed.

Your feedback and comments are welcome.

Negotiations with Amiga Inc's Tom Schmidt: The Man at the Helm of Amiga.

COSA have maintained our open line to Tom Schmidt at Amiga. We thought we should
share some broad background information with our members, and provide our
assessment and perspective of the man who is now at the helm of Amiga, based on
our own experiences and dialogues with him.

We are aware that our president is probably one of only a handful of Amigans who
have had the opportunity to speak to Amiga President Tom Schmidt since he took
over the helm of Amiga in September. We thought Amigans might appreciate hearing
our perspective on both Mr Schmidt as a person, and on Amiga as a company.

First of all, one thing is clear: behind the scenes, Mr Schmidt is a very busy
man. There is clearly a lot of activity going on behind the scenes, and Amiga
are hard at work on their projects. For Amiga at least, it seems to be a case of
"business as usual." We have spoken briefly to a number of people inside Amiga
Inc, including a programmer - so yes, they're definately working on something.
But in the words of that same programmer "it doesn't have to do with the classic
Amiga, [and] I don't know about that, you will have to speak to someone else."

Mr Schmidt himself is not the unreasonable tyrant that some have painted him to
be. We have found him to be a polite and very reasonable negotiator, who is much
misunderstood. His decisions relating to the future of Amiga as a company are
based on solid, practical business reasons, and we suspect on Gateway's need for
Amiga to be their subsidary focusing on Information Appliances.

It is our feeling and belief that Gateway never intended for Amiga to deliver a
next-generation Amiga computer system, or operating system, or sucessor to the
traditional line of Amiga computers, but to create operating system software
(Operating Environments) for the emerging Information Appliances market, a
potentially multi-billion dollar industry in which Amiga looks set to become a
key player.

In this context, Tom Schmidt as President and CEO of Amiga is merely following
the plan that Gateway had originally intended for Amiga as a company, as a
strategic software group targeting the next generation of computing devices.

That said, Mr Schmidt is aware of the concerns of the Amiga community and is
sympathetic to our concerns. As indicated in his most recent executive update,
Mr Schmidt wishes to find a solution that will address the needs of the Amiga
community. We believe, from his words and from our own dealings with him, that
he is most sincere when he says this. He admires the fact we have "hung in
there" through thick and thin, and in his own words, "[we] deserve better". It
is simply the case that Amiga Inc's mandate from Gateway does not and cannot
include directly tackling the needs of the Amiga community. Amiga Inc has most
likely been told to focus completely on information appliances.

But it remains the case that Amiga and Gateway own a number of patents and
trademarks from the "classic" Amiga portfolio that are no longer of any use to
them, unused and "gathering dust". They certainly seem willing to discuss
options on how this technology can be used.

It is on this basis that COSA have been negotiating with Amiga.

Our proposal is that open-sourcing the Amiga operating system frees the
operating system in ways essential to the long-term survival, expansion and
growth of our platform, and that both the Amiga community and Amiga Inc can
share in the rewards (and revenue stream) and new flexibility and freedom that
Open Source can bring.

Our negotiations with Amiga have focused on strategies that could be of benefit
to Amiga Inc if they open-source the classic Amiga OS. We have put them forward
as common-sense business proposals that are of little risk, and much potential
benefit, to Amiga, and of great benefit to the Amiga OS's long-term survival and
growth, and thus good for the Amiga community. We proposed that this would lead
to much positive publicity for the Amiga OS, and for Amiga the company, and that
opening the OS and releasing it to the common ownership of the Amiga community
would be a show of good faith on the part of Amiga Inc, to the classic Amiga
community.

The response from Amiga has been to allow COSA an open line to Tom Schmidt's
office, to negotiate and discuss proposals with them. I would describe our
negotiations as polite, cordial and productive.

The Amiga community needs to realise that Tom Schmidt is not the villain some
paint him to be. At worst, he is a businessman who has been forced to make
difficult, unpopular decisions. I certainly do not believe the intent was a
malicious one. If this was the intent, he would not even be considering COSA's
proposals or discuss ways Amiga could make amends for their recent decisions.
But they have. COSA has an open line to Tom Schmidt, and discussions on both
sides I have found to be fair, professional and productive. He has not
completely cut off contact with the Amiga community - he maintains an open line
to those who show an interest in productive, reasoned negotiation. He is a fine
businessman who has been too harshly judged in my opinion. While his decisions
have not been favourable for the community, I suspect many of these were forced
by circumstance, or due to orders and mandates from above in the Gateway
hierarchy. It is thus not fair to blame Mr Schmidt for these decisions, and I
feel he should be judged not by decisions forced by circumstance, but how he
responds to fair, reasonable and common-sense proposals brought to him by the
Amiga community. I have a feeling that Amigans may be pleasantly surprised to
find that Mr Schmidt is very reasonable and will listen to good proposals, and I
suspect he will support causes that advance the classic Amiga provided we
respect Amiga's right to pursue it's own business strategies.

I realise the above may not be what many people want to hear, but I highly
suspect it is the truth, based on my own experiences in talks with Tom Schmidt
and Amiga Inc, and from other information that has been shared with me. It is
all too easy to blame the President and CEO of a company when we don't like what
they are doing. This is fair where the President and CEO enjoys completely
autonomy and the ability to shape the company to his own desire, but I suspect
in the case of Tom Schmidt he must operate Amiga Inc within certain forced
paramaters and boundaries set by Gateway.

I suspect these boundaries would allow Tom Schmidt to negotiate with Amiga
organisations and consider proposals for using the classic Amiga technology, but
bind him from taking on any classic projects of his own at Amiga Inc.
Negotiations with Amiga and Tom Schmidt may yet prove fruitful, and if they do,
we'll know COSA was right about him. Let's just hope he says "yes" to our
proposal. I remain optimisticly hopeful that something can be negotiated with
Amiga, and we will continue to hold talks with them for as long as there is a
sign of light at the end of the tunnel. We'll keep you updated on our progress.

-- Steve Crietzman, 24/12/99
President, COSA/Open Amiga Group
