@node not38 "QUAKE NEWS"

                                   QUAKE NEWS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

On December 21st, ID Software released the source code of winquake, glquake,
quakeworld and glquakeworld under GNU Public License (GPL) and made them
available by ftp. Some week after that, we have already two legal Quake ports
for Amiga.

The first one is called AWinQuake, and it has been developed by Peter McGavin,
who did the best Doom port for Amiga: ADoom. AWinQuake is based on winquake, due
to the fact that winquake is well written and extremely portable, so it didn't
take long to get it working on an Amiga by cutting and pasting code from other
projects.

FEATURES:

   - Both 68k and PPC versions are provided.
   - Both versions are OS-friendly and multitask.
   - Both versions put up an ASL requester for the ScreenMode.
   - awinquakeppc uses Joseph Fenton's PPC c2p routine from ADoomPPC and triple
     buffering in AGA modes.
   - Sound effects are included. Also CD audio for music works if you use
     ClickBoom's AmigaQuake CDROM. You need cdplayer.library (from Aminet) for
     this.
   - Networking for TCP/IP is included.
   - awinquakeppc works with either PowerUp or WarpOS. With WarpOS, use Frank
     Wille's ppc emulation library.
   - awinquakeppc is mostly compiled with SAS/C scppc. However, the innermost
     rendering routines are compiled with ppc-amigaos-gcc. This results in a
     small speedup (about 3%) over compiling everything with scppc.
   - His modified source code should still compile for Linux (APUS), Solaris,
     Win95, etc, with no changes --- untested.
   - Speeds over 37 fps have been observed for "timedemo demo2" in 320x200 on a
     233 MHz PPC Amiga 3000 with CyberVisionPPC.
   - Added a -fps option, but see the note below about bus speed before you
     believe the numbers you see.

LIMITATIONS:

   - The 68k version is much slower than ClickBoom's commercial version.
   - Only the PPC version has optimised c2p for AGA. In fact the 68k version is
     not recommended. Buy Clickboom's version instead.
   - Only keyboard control. No mouse, joystick or joypad yet.
   - No AHI.
   - No very much optimisation.

REQUIREMENTS:

   - A 68020+ Amiga running at least OS 3.1, with at least about 16 Mb of
     fastmem.
   - An FPU is required.
   - You need either a gfx-card or AGA. ECS alone is not sufficient.
   - A TCP/IP stack is required for networking, e.g, AmiTCP or Miami. An
     ethernet card is strongly recommended.
   - A stack size of 500000 bytes. I'm not sure what the minimum stack size is.
     150000 bytes is definitely too small.
   - An MMU is neither required nor used.
   - You need cdplayer.library from Aminet, or start with -nocdaudio. The game
     searches for Clickboom's CDROM for cdaudio (volume name "QUAKE".)
   - You need the Quake 1 PAK files and other support files from either a
     commercial or shareware version of Quake. Assuming you've already
     installed AmigaQuake or a PC version, put awinquake or awinquakeppc in the
     same directory as the original quake executable.

You can download the Peter's port from Aminet:

   - http://ftp.uni-paderborn.de/aminet/aminet/game/shoot/awinquake.lha (572374
     bytes)

On the other hand, Steffen Haeuser and Frank Ville have released a first Beta
version of the Quake 1.09 and QuakeWorld Port. The Beta Version includes
binaries for WarpUP (vbcc-WarpUP compiled) and PowerUP (vbcc-PowerUP compiled)
of QuakePPC. The list of features includes:

   - GFX Board and AGA Support
   - Support for PIP (Picasso 96) and WB Window
   - Double- and Triplebuffering
   - Sound
   - CD Audio Support
   - Mouse, Joypad and Joystick Support
   - In-Game Video-Options
   - Network Support
   - QuakeWorld Support (Client and Server)

This is only a Beta version, later it is planned to enhance this version, to
release a 68k version and much later to add Warp3D support (with the help of
MiniGL) and a comfortable GUI.

Anyway, they are looking for help, so anybody who wants to overtake some part of
the stuff, feel free to contact Steffen at MagicSN@Birdland.es.bawue.de. If
several coders work together, things might speed up to the "perfect Quake Port".

You can download this version from:

   - http://devnull.owl.de/~frank/quake_e.html (Very Slow)
   - http://members.es.tripod.de/debugger/RTGMaster/download.html (Recommended)
